            "question": {
                "text": "Consider a simple undirected weighted graph G, all \nof whose edge weights are distinct. Which of the \nfollowing statements about the minimum spanning \ntrees of G is/are TRUE?",
                "images": [],
                "latex": [],
                "tables": []
            },
            "options": [
                {
                    "id": "A",
                    "text": "The edge with the second smallest weight is \n\nalways part of any minimum spanning tree of G.",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "B",
                    "text": "One or both of the edges with the third smallest \nand the fourth smallest weights are part of any \nminimum spanning tree of G .",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "C",
                    "text": "Suppose S\nV\n\nbe such that S \\neq ϕ and S \\neq V . \nConsider the edge with the minimum weight \nsuch that one of its vertices is in S and the other \nin V \\ S. Such an edge will always be part of any \nminimum spanning tree of G .",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "D",
                    "text": "G can have multiple minimum spanning trees.",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                }
            ],
            "correctAnswer": [
                "A",
                "B",
                "C"
            ],
            "solution": {
                "text": "• Since G has Exactly One MST, as all the edge \nweights are unique so the statement in option (a) \nis correct. \n• As already the given graph G has distinct as \nweights, the third and fourth smallest edge \nweights will always be a part of MST. \n• This is a popular and basic property of Minimum \nSpanning Tree, known as \"Cut Property.\" The cut \nconsider for the MST problem. \"Cut Property\" \nand \"Cycle Property\" are basic theorems.",
                "images": [
                    "assets/Algorithms/ALGO_Miscellaneous_Topics_P51_X5530.png",
                    "assets/Algorithms/ALGO_Miscellaneous_Topics_P51_X5534.png",
                    "assets/Algorithms/ALGO_Miscellaneous_Topics_P51_X5536.png"
                ],
                "latex": [],
                "tables": []
            }
        },
